{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Cache keys generated from identical query parameters are always identical, and keys from different parameters never collide.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is a deterministic key-derivation correctness property at a single function/object boundary (parameter canonicalization + hashing/serialization). No real I/O or module handoff is required to expose the core failure.","test_description":"Unit/property-style test for `makeCacheKey(params)`: assert equal keys for semantically identical parameter maps (including reordered keys), and assert unequal keys for a large adversarial set of different parameter combinations. Include edge cases (nulls, arrays, nested objects, type distinctions like `\"1\"` vs `1`).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The TTL for a cache entry is computed correctly based on the data category's configured freshness rule (e.g., user profiles = 5 minutes, product catalog = 1 hour).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"TTL mapping from category/config to duration is pure business logic. Real infrastructure is not needed to catch incorrect rule application.","test_description":"Unit test `computeTTL(category, config, now?)` with table-driven cases for each category rule, unknown-category fallback behavior, and boundary values (zero/negative/missing TTL config). Verify returned TTL duration exactly matches configured freshness policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.84,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When memory usage exceeds the configured threshold, the eviction strategy switches from LRU to LFU as specified in the configuration.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"The failure boundary is the handoff between memory-usage source, configuration, and strategy-selection state. A unit test of selector logic alone can miss wiring/state-update defects.","test_description":"Integration test wiring cache manager + memory monitor adapter + config loader. Start below threshold and assert active policy is LRU; then drive reported memory above threshold and assert policy changes to LFU and subsequent eviction uses LFU counters. Also verify no switch when threshold is not crossed.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.28,"Integration":0.66,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A write to the underlying PostgreSQL table invalidates all cache entries whose keys match the affected rows.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This behavior is about DB-write-to-cache-invalidation interaction. The key risk is cross-module propagation (write path/change detection/key matching), which mocks can hide. A local DB-backed integration test is sufficient; no external network/service behavior is inherently required.","test_description":"Integration test with local PostgreSQL test instance/schema and real cache layer wiring: seed rows + warm cache entries, execute update/delete/insert on target table through the data access path, then assert matching cache keys are removed while unrelated keys remain. Include multi-row write to verify fan-out invalidation.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.74,"System":0.2,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The eviction policy removes the correct entries — least-recently-used under LRU, least-frequently-used under LFU — when the cache is full.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core eviction correctness is algorithmic behavior of cache/policy data structures under controlled access patterns; no infrastructure dependency is needed for real failure detection.","test_description":"Unit tests for policy engine/cache container with fixed capacity: for LRU, create recency pattern and assert oldest-by-access-time is evicted; for LFU, create frequency pattern (including tie-break rule) and assert least-used key is evicted. Verify counters/recency metadata update on read/write before eviction.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.82,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}}]}
